## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

### Key Problems in the Original Code

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 8 — it was removed entirely.
2. **`Thread.Interrupt()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 8 — also removed.
3. **Race condition**: multiple `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne`/`Reset` lose items — only one `Dequeue` per signal.
4. **No graceful shutdown** mechanism — relies on removed APIs.

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _runTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        var reader = _channel.Reader;
        // ReadAllAsync yields items as they arrive; exits when
        // the channel is completed or the token is cancelled.
        await foreach (var item in reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        // 1. Signal the channel is done — reader loop will finish
        //    after draining remaining items.
        _channel.Writer.Complete();

        // 2. Give it time to drain, then force-cancel.
        if (_runTask is not null)
        {
            using var timeout = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
            try
            {
                await _runTask.WaitAsync(timeout.Token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                // Drain timed out — cancel the loop.
                _cts?.Cancel();
                try { await _runTask; } catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
            }
        }

        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // your processing logic
    }
}
```

### If You Need a Synchronous (non-async) Version

Replace `Channel<T>` with `BlockingCollection<T>`, which is the direct modern equivalent of the manual queue+signal pattern:

```csharp
using System.Collections.Concurrent;

public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop) { IsBackground = true };
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        // GetConsumingEnumerable blocks until items arrive
        // and exits when CompleteAdding() is called.
        foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable())
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding();       // unblocks the loop
        _thread?.Join(5000);           // wait for drain
        _queue.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

### Migration Pitfalls Summary

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 Status | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | `CancellationToken` / `Channel.Complete()` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | `CancellationToken` |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` | Works but error-prone | `Channel<T>` or `BlockingCollection<T>` |
| `Thread` for background work | Works but less efficient | `Task.Run` + `async/await` |

**Prefer the `Channel<T>` version** — it's the idiomatic .NET 8 approach, integrates with `async/await`, and avoids thread-pool starvation from blocking calls.
